    himi.c:22:13: warning: ‘temp’ may be used uninitialized in this function [-Wmaybe-uninitialized]
                 strcpy(temp, str[i]);
                 ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

An uninitialized pointer is always good for an access violation (or segmentation fault, on Unix), as you&#39;re trying to access some random memory that isn&#39;t yours, and the operating system slaps you on the wrist (i.e., terminates your misbehaving program).

That said, when you sort strings, you usually don&#39;t `strcpy` the strings around in memory, you just switch around the pointers. This is much faster, as you only need to modify pointers. It also avoids crashes with different string lengths: your code would try to copy the &quot;JavaScript&quot; (10 characters) into &quot;Java&quot; (4 characters). Writing in memory areas you&#39;re not supposed to write can crash your program (if you&#39;re lucky) or you just overwrite other variables and notice only much later (have fun debugging that).

